Continuity of Learning and COVID-19 Response Plan (“Plan”)
Application Template
 
As a result of COVID-19 and the closing of school buildings for the 2019-2020 School Year, school districts must submit a Continuity of Learning and COVID-19 Response Plan (“Plan”) in order to continue to receive state aid for operations. Although schools are closed and not providing in-person instruction, teaching and learning must continue. Michigan educators have been called to provide our students with continued learning. 
 
There are varied states of readiness to provide continuity in learning among districts. Even within districts of multiple school sites, there are varied states of readiness. It is expected that schools will provide instruction at a distance using a variety of methods that meet local needs, including printed materials, phone contact, email, virtual learning, or a combination to meet student needs. We should avoid assuming that continuity in learning can only occur through online means. 
 
While many educators have been providing distance learning opportunities, the Governor’s Executive Order (EO 2020-35) requires all schools to begin providing learning opportunities for all students no later than April 28, 2020. Districts who are able to begin their plans earlier are encouraged to do so. 
 
Each District shall submit a single completed Assurance Document, Budget Outline, and Continuity of Learning Plan to its Intermediate School District. Each Public School Academy shall submit a completed Assurance Document, Budget Outline, and Continuity of Learning Plan to its Authorizer. A single Application should be filed for the district rather than multiple applications for individual schools within a district. The following items are required for the application which may be submitted beginning April 8, 2020:

Assurances Document
Continuity of Learning Plan
Budget Outline

 











Continuity of Learning and COVID-19 Response Plan (“Plan”)
Guiding Principles 

As Districts and Public School Academies complete the Assurances and Continuity of Learning Plans, they should consider utilizing the following principles to guide their work:
 
Keep Students at the Center
Intentional outreach to continue building relationships and maintain connections. Help students feel safe and valued. At minimum, plan to do the following:
Plan for Student Learning: Build on each student’s strengths, interests, and needs and use this knowledge to positively affect learning.
Develop a Weekly Plan and Schedule: Offer routines and structures for consistency and for the balancing of think time, work time, and play time for health and well-being.
Contact Families: Partner to support student learning through ongoing communication and collaboration. This will not look the same for every student and family—safety remains the priority. Provide translations as necessary.
 
Design Learning for Equity and Access
Plan and deliver content in multiple ways so all students can access learning.
Teach Content: Set goals using knowledge of each student, content area standards, and of Michigan Merit Curriculum.
Deliver Flexible Instruction: Consider how to deliver content depending on tools and resources accessible to each student. Alternative modes of instruction may include use of online learning, telephone communications, email, virtual instruction, videos, slideshows, project-based learning, use of instructional packets, or a combination to meet diverse student needs.
Engage Families: Communicate with families about engagement strategies to support students as they access the learning. Families are critical partners. Provide translations as necessary.
 
Assess Student Learning
Manage and monitor student learning and plan what’s next for learning including the potential need for summer and supplemental learning.

Assurances

Date Submitted: April 8, 2020

Name of District: Saline Area Schools

Address of District: 7265 Saline-Ann Arbor Road, Saline, MI 48176

District Code Number: 81120

Email Address of the District: gradens@salineschools.org

Name of Intermediate School District: Washtenaw Intermediate

Name of Authorizing Body (if applicable): 

 
This Assurance document needs to be returned to your Intermediate School District or, for Public School Academies, your Authorizing Body with your Continuity of Learning Plan and Budget Outline beginning April 8, 2020 to indicate that the District will adopt a plan to ensure continuous learning for all students through the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. 

Districts should submit a single district plan that relates to all of their schools. 
 
The applicant hereby provides assurance it will follow the requirements for a Plan for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year:
Applicant assures that all student learning will take place under the direction of a teacher of record for each student enrolled in the district. 
Applicant assures that it will continue to pay school employees during the balance of the 2019-2020 school year under the same terms and conditions established prior to the school closure order period.
Applicant assures that the Plan was developed in collaboration with district administrators, school board members, teachers, and local bargaining units.
Applicant assures that food distribution has been arranged for or provided for eligible students. 
Applicant assures coordination between applicant and Intermediate School District in which the District/PSA is located to mobilize disaster relief child care centers. 
Applicant assures that to the extent practicable the District/PSA will in good faith provide students with IEPs/Section 504 Plans the opportunity to participate in learning consistent with existing plans.
Applicant assures that Continuity of Learning and COVID-19 Response Plan, Assurance Document, and Budget Outline will be posted immediately following approval to the District’s/PSA’s website.



Continuity of Learning and COVID-19 Response Plan (“Plan”)
 
The goal of a Continuity of Learning Plan and COVID-19 Response Plan is to ensure that each District or Public School Academy is providing, to the best of its ability, each student with alternative modes of instruction to help them stay on pace in their learning. This application recognizes that there is no “one-size-fits-all” solution; multiple means of engaging students and supporting families may be necessary that may vary by grade level, school building, or student population served.

For the purposes of the Plan, “district” refers to school districts and public school academies.

Date Submitted: April 8, 2020

Name of District: Saline Area Schools

Address of District: 7265 Saline-Ann Arbor Road, Saline, MI 48176

District Code Number: 81120

Email Address of the District Superintendent: gradens@salineschools.org

Name of Intermediate School District: Washtenaw Intermediate

Name of Authorizing Body (if applicable): 
 

In accordance with Executive Order 2020-35 a Plan must include all of the following parts:

Please describe the methods the district will use to provide alternative modes of instruction other than in-person instruction and a summary of materials each pupil and the pupil’s parents or guardians will need to access meaningfully the alternative modes of instruction included in the Plan. If the Plan relies on electronic instruction, the Plan must ensure to the extent feasible that pupils have access to a connected device capable of accessing the electronic instruction and must not penalize a pupil for the pupil’s inability to fully participate.
“Alternative modes of instruction” means modes of pupil instruction, other than in-person instruction, that may include, without limitation, partnerships with other districts or intermediate districts or community colleges or institutions of higher education, use of vendors, use of online learning, telephone communications, email, virtual instruction, videos, slideshows, project-based learning, use of instructional packets, or a hybrid of multiple modes of learning that still promote recommended practices for social distancing to mitigate the spread of COVID-19.

DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":8722,"s":"District/ PSA Response:
Alternative Modes of Instruction
Saline Area Schools will be providing distance learning in a number of ways in order to support ALL Saline students. General Education teachers, Special Education teachers, and English Language tutors will be using virtual instruction as the primary means of providing distance learning, support, and outreach for students. For students who prefer or need print material to access the distance learning experiences, print materials such as learning packets, textbooks and guide books that parallel the instruction/learning virtual opportunities will be used. For students who were already engaged in Edgenuity, Michigan Virtual, etc online instruction, their mode of instruction will continue in the same manner as before the COVID-19 closure.

Summary of Materials Needed
To be successful with these modes of instruction, students engaging in the distance learning plan virtually will need access to a digital device and a reliable internet connection; students engaging via print version will require the printed materials.

Beginning the week of March 23rd, SAS scheduled ongoing "tech pick-up" events in order to distribute devices to students/families who indicated a need. The District was able to distribute over 1000 devices (iPads and Chromebooks). The District has also established a central location for print material pick up. Tech distribution and print material pick up will continue throughout the implementation of the SAS distance learning plan. For families without transportation, door-to-door delivery of devices or printed material is provided. 

Access and Connection to a Device
To ensure access to the internet, the SAS technology team has set up mobile hot spots in the parking lots of three of SAS schools for families and students to access as needed. Further, the tech team is working to mobilize hot spots to families that cannot afford internet access. The District did perform a tech device and access survey three weeks ago to better learn about the needs in the homes of students throughout the District.

No Penalty for Inability to Participate
Students who are not able to participate or who choose not to participate for any reason will not be penalized. However, relevant staff such as the classroom teacher, building administrator or assigned counselor will reach out to all students (families) who are not participating to check in on their social emotional well-being to see if there is anything that the teacher, administrator or District can do to help them participate.


Please describe the methods the district will use to keep pupils at the center of educational activities, including outreach to continue building relationships and maintain connections, and to help pupils feel safe and valued.
District/ PSA Response:
Keeping Pupils at the Center of Educational Activities
Saline Area Schools has established a graduate profile (the SAS Compass) that calls for the intentional implementation of 8 student attributes throughout the course of an SAS student’s career in the District. These student attributes include all of the following:

Although this COVID-19 Pandemic has caused an extremely disruptive educational environment and will expose a number of equity issues that we will need to address, it does present an opportunity for our students and staff to truly embody all the student attributes within the SAS Compass.

Saline Area Schools will establish a multi-layered approach to keeping students at the center of educational activities and continuing to build relationships and maintain connections – district-wide, building-based, and teacher/classroom centered. Ongoing communication regarding updates, plans, and available support has been and will be provided via the District resource page, social media platforms, direct email, School Messenger for direct whole-district calls, and 1:1 phone calls. Further, all of this work is being done as the District considers a lens of equity. District staff will account for the inequities that exist throughout the SAS student body such as housing situations, accessibility, and family situations.

At the district level, central administration will provide general overviews, offer supportive whole-district messaging such as “Saline Strong”/#SalineStrong, and communicate supports in place such as food distribution, social services, and mental health resources.

At the building level, building administrators will provide weekly updates, offer supportive building messaging, and communicate whole building culture or community events and opportunities such as inspirational videos, spirit weeks, one-book-one-school, etc.

At the teacher/classroom level, teachers will balance social-emotional and academic needs via a structure that is developmentally appropriate per grade level. As part of this, they will create meaningful instructional plans and learning opportunities, engage with students on both an academic and social-emotional level, offer choices for learning and engagement, provide feedback for submitted work, and promote class community building such as video conferencing, peer check-ins, and office hours.

To ensure all students are connected, teachers and ancillary service providers, as well as building principals will keep active spreadsheets to monitor student engagement and seek regular feedback via digital (Google Forms) or non-digital (phone call) check-ins. If a student is not engaging, phone calls/emails will be made to determine why a student is not able to engage and adjustments to the distance learning plan for that particular student will be made. Further, in order to better support special student populations, teachers, principals, counselors, social workers, school psychologists, case managers, EL tutors, etc. will all be checking in on students (families) on a regular basis to make sure that their individual education plans (IEPS) are implemented to the fullest extent possible and that individualized needs are met, to the extent possible through distance learning. 

Here are examples of various learning plans being put in place at the various levels throughout the District:
Grade 2

Saline Middle School
Saline High School


Please describe the district’s plans to deliver content in multiple ways so that all pupils can access learning.
District/ PSA Response:
Multiple Methods of Content Delivery
SAS recognizes that distance learning will take many different forms in order to meet the learners’ needs based on their current home situation, family dynamics and needs of the student. Teachers primarily will deliver instruction and content via their learning management system. For students who do not have access OR are not able to learn online, paper/pencil alternatives will be provided. Universal supports such as audio options, visual supports, and teacher modeling will be woven holistically in order to meet the needs of students in special populations such as students with IEPs, 504, or language learners. If universal supports are not sufficient to meet the exceptional needs of a student the district will use the IEP process to evaluate the need for compensatory education services on an individual basis.

Examples of platforms for student engagement:
Seesaw, Summit Learning, Google Classroom, Flip Grid, Youtube stories, Teacher / Service Provider created modeling videos, Powerschool Learning, and other Online vendors . Further, many teachers will be using Zoom and Google Hangouts as a video chat service to deliver content and connect with students. Print materials as needed.


Please describe the district’s plans to manage and monitor learning by pupils.
District/ PSA Response:
Manage and Monitor Learning
The District is committed to designing a plan in which ALL students are able to receive credit and/or grade advancement. With this commitment, teachers, in conjunction with district administration and instructional designers, are collaborating to design weekly learning experiences centered on essential skills and concepts.

Assignment check points and formative feedback
Self evaluation and goal setting
Quick formative checks such as Kahoot, Quizlet, Actively Learn
Use of Zoom to inquire about progress
Use of checklists/rubrics to guide feedback
Use of weekly journals or reflections
 
For students with digital access, online vendors will be used to enable teachers to engage with students in learning, post assignments, provide formative feedback for submitted work, and monitor progress. For students who do not have internet access, paper/pencil materials will be distributed on a weekly basis and a system will be in place to monitor progress phone calls, and/or a pick-up/drop-off method through the SAS Transportation Department.

For secondary credit-bearing classes, Saline Area Schools will be issuing credit/no credit. Credit - COVID /No Record - COVID will be the two marks indicated on a student’s transcript at the conclusion of T3. Since grades and grading in general are not equitable during this time, no traditional grades will be given.

There is an expected level of engagement from SAS 9th, 10th, 11th grade students to participate in the learning plan that is developed by Saline teachers. In order for students to receive “credit” for their third trimester courses in the 2019/2020 school year, the District expects student engagement to take place. Teachers will determine the “markers” for credit, knowing that options for earning credit should be accessible to all students, including special populations. Should a teacher notice that a student is not engaging or completing work, all efforts will be made to adjust the learning plans, including options for earning credit, per the student’s individual needs. 

Students who previously were enrolled in online coursework will continue along the same learning plan (grades and credits will be awarded at the conclusion of the course). 

Seniors Expectation: Senior students will be notified by their counselor if there is a class they need to take for graduation. If students do not need the class to graduate, they will not be required to participate or engage. However, the District does want to continue offering the classes for engagement and social-emotional check-ins for students.

Note: As necessary, instruction for the Fall of 2020 and Winter/Spring 2021 will be differentiated in order to incorporate missed curriculum. 


Please attach a budget outline estimating additional expenditures associated with the Plan and sources of revenue to pay for those expenditures.
District/ PSA Response:
Budget *See attached budget estimation 
Saline staff are going to be using Zoom as a primary method of delivering face-to-face conferencing with students. This professional subscription for the District will cost around $17,500 (see attached quote)

There will be additional costs accrued for compensatory education for students with IEPS if the District was not able to fully implement the IEP through emergency remote teaching. These costs will be $95,000

Finally, for those students who do not have access at the elementary level, the District will offer Think Stretch student workbooks (K-6th grade). These workbooks provide a close connection to SAS curriculum and will provide more independent structure for students. $13 for each workbook @200 students = $2600

Technology costs to replace and fix devices being used by our students for distance learning during the COVID-19 Pandemic. We have over 1200 devices (iPads, Chromebooks) distributed throughout the community = $80,000
In order to provide support for students who need additional summer programming, the District would like to allocate $25,000 to support coursework and programs for the summer months.
Applications and site licenses for digital learning platforms = $10,000

Please describe the manner in which district administrators, board members, teachers, and any representatives of teachers collaborated in development of the Plan.
District/ PSA Response:
Collaboration Team
SAS had a team consisting of the following people working on this plan:
Brian Boze, Katie Huang, Carl Spina - Teachers and SEA (Saline Educational Association) Representatives
Heidi Pfannes - Saline Board of Education President
Betty Rosen-Leacher, Elementary Principal
Megan DeGrand - Elementary Assistant Principal
Alex Schukow - Middle School Assistant Principal
Theresa Stager - High School Assistant Principal
Kara Davis - Instructional Designer
Ryan Rowe - Principal, Southwest Washtenaw Consortium
Carol Melcher - Saline Alternative High School Principal
Molly Garcia - Director of Student Services
Steve Laatsch - Assistant Superintendent of Instruction
Chris Cummings - Parent 

The team met three times in which they did the following:
Developed the plan
Revised the plan
Cross-referenced the plan with the MAISA document
Created a checklist to determine if the SAS plan met all the requirements within the template
Submitted the plan

Please describe the methods the district will use to notify pupils and parents or guardians of the Plan.
District/ PSA Response:
Notification to Pupils/Families
Email, website, and blog post messages have been distributed to all families over the past month keeping families up to speed on the rapidly changing plans of the District to engage students in distance learning. With the signing of the Executive Order, this learning plan is being developed and will be communicated to families, students and community members via email, district website, blog posts, social media, US Mail, and phone calls for families who do not have internet access.

District/ PSA Response:
Plan Starting Date
April 13, 2020


Please describe the assistance, to the extent feasible, to pupils enrolled in any postsecondary dual enrollment courses under Public Act 160 of 1996, as amended, MCL 388.511 to 388.524, and Career and Technical Preparation Act, 258 PA 2000, as amended, MCL 388.1901 to 388.1913, in completing the courses during the 2019-2020 school year.
District/ PSA Response:
Dual Enrollment / CTE Course Completion Plan
SAS has dual enrollment students at various schools such as SAS, WCC, Eastern Michigan, etc. and these schools have moved their courses online. The District is following up with students to make sure that they have access to complete these courses in that capacity. The District provided Chromebooks for students who need greater access.

For CTE, SAS is aligning efforts with consortium districts for CTE. This includes the ability for some of District “certificate bearing” CTE programs to operate online for part of their instructional model.


Please describe how the district will continue to provide or arrange for continuation of food distribution to eligible pupils.
District/ PSA Response:
Food Distribution
SAS Food Services Department Providing Meals for Families: Beginning this week (on April 7th and April 10th), the Saline Area Schools Food Services Department will be providing meals two days per week on Tuesdays and Fridays.
 
With the extended school closure, Saline Area Schools has developed a food distribution program that will complement the incredible support already being provided by Saline Area Social Services. The District recognizes that there are students in need of nutritious meals and is prepared to provide these for SAS families. 
Beginning next week, the Saline Area Schools Food Services Department will be providing meals two days per week on Tuesdays and Fridays. Below are the specific details: 
Dates: The first two distribution dates are Tuesday, April 7th and Friday, April 10th, 2020. In the weeks to follow, Tuesday and Friday distribution will continue until further notice.

DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":25293,"s":"Who: Families in need can receive food for all children under 18, and anyone under 26 with special needs. 
Curbside pick up location: Saline High School, Auditorium Entrance/Bus Loop 
Time: 11:00 a.m. - 2:30 p.m., both Tuesday and Friday 
Meal Count: On Tuesday, each package will include both breakfast and lunch for three days. On Friday, each package will include both breakfast and lunch for four days. 
To best serve the community and prepare meal packages, the District requested that all interested families fill out THIS FORM. 

If families are unable to pick up food independently at the pick-up location, the SAS transportation department will deliver the food to the home.

Please confirm that the district will continue to pay school employees while redeploying staff to provide meaningful work in the context of the Plan, subject to any applicable requirements of a collective bargaining agreement.
District/ PSA Response:
Payment
We are confirming that Saline Area Schools will continue to pay school employees while redeploying staff to provide meaningful work in the context of the Plan, subject to any applicable requirements of a collective bargaining agreement. 


Provide describe how the district will evaluate the participation of pupils in the Plan.
District/ PSA Response:
Evaluate Participation
The District is committed to designing a plan in which ALL students are able to participate. District staff will use the continuum of engagement to evaluate participation, most importantly identifying students who are somewhat engaged and not engaged. For students who are NOT engaging, teachers, principals, counselors, school psychologists, social workers, case managers, EL tutors, etc. will all be checking in on these students (families) on a regular basis to make sure that their needs are met. 

Continuum of Engagement
Not Engaged
Somewhat Engaged
Mostly Engaged
Highly Engaged
Student has not engaged in any portion of the learning plan over the course of 5 days.
Student is inconsistently engaged in the Learning Plan; participation is less than weekly and/or related learning opportunities are only partially completed.
Student regularly engages in most but not all of the Learning Plan - participating weekly with most learning opportunities.
Student always engages in all portions of the Learning Plan - participating in and completing all related learning opportunities.
Supports Required
Supports Suggested
Considerations

*The classroom teacher should have attempted contact prior to starting Step 1.
Step 1: Student identified on building spreadsheet as not engaging for 5 straight days, 
Step 2: Building Principal emails or calls the family to check in on the student and see how the family is doing, 
Step 3: After identifying the needs of the student (family) a modified learning plan is developed in consultation with the teacher (s), etc.
 Teacher contacts the student/family directly
 Identifying the needs of the student (family)
 Adjust the learning plan to better suit the student’s needs
 Offer (or point out) extension activities/work should student (family) want to take advantage of additional opportunities


Adjustments will be made to these learning plans to better meet the needs of students who are not engaging in the initial plan. Compensatory services may be offered to certain students if it is deemed appropriate per their IEP. Students who can’t engage or who choose to disengage will not be penalized, may receive an incomplete or no grade for that course/content work at the secondary level for credit-bearing classes and may be asked to repeat the class.

Secondary Credit-Bearing Classes

For secondary credit-bearing classes, Saline Area Schools will be issuing credit/no credit. Credit - COVID /No Record - COVID will be the two marks indicated on a student’s transcript at the conclusion of T3. Since grades and grading in general are not equitable during this time, no traditional grades will be given.

There is an expected level of engagement from SAS 9th, 10th, 11th grade students to participate in the learning plan that is developed by Saline teachers. In order for students to receive “credit” for their third trimester courses in the 2019/2020 school year, the District expects student engagement to take place. Teachers will determine the “markers” for credit, knowing that options for earning credit should be accessible to all students, including special populations. Should a teacher notice that a student is not engaging or completing work, all efforts will be made to adjust the learning plans, including options for earning credit, per the student’s individual needs. 

Students who previously were enrolled in online coursework will continue along the same learning plan (grades and credits will be awarded at the conclusion of the course). 

Seniors Expectation: Senior students will be notified by their counselor if there is a class they need to take for graduation. If students do not need the class to graduate, they will not be required to participate or engage. However, the District does want to continue offering the classes for engagement and social-emotional check-ins for students.


Please describe how the district will provide mental health supports to pupils affected by a state of emergency or state of disaster prompted by COVID-19.
District/ PSA Response:
Mental Health Support
Classroom Teachers, Administrators, Counselors, Social Workers and School Psychologists will be reaching out to students (and families) on a regular basis.

Frequent checks for students who were struggling before the COVID-19 will be made to see how they are doing and respond to any more struggles as a result of the Pandemic. Resources will be shared with students and families to support mental health and socio-emotional well being for all students. This may include social stories, videos, articles, phone calls, as well as peer support groups in zoom or google chat.

Guiding questions for support will be provided for therapeutic staff to use with families.

Further, social workers, school psychologists, teacher consultants, and resource room teachers will be monitoring their caseload on a weekly basis to provide the necessary support that their students need.
NOTE: Tuition based and GSRP early childhood programs will continue to interact as the District wants to support the mental health of these students within the District as well as the K-12 population.

Please describe how the district will support the efforts of the intermediate district in which the district is located to mobilize disaster relief child care centers as described in Executive Order 2020-16 or any executive order that follow it.
District/ PSA Response:
Disaster Relief Childcare Centers
The Saline Area Schools will support the efforts of the Washtenaw Intermediate School District with child care centers as described.


Optional question: 
Does the District to adopt a balanced calendar instructional program for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year? Does the District plan to adopt a balanced calendar instructional program for the 2020-2021 school year? 
District/ PSA Response:
Balanced Calendar
The District does not plan to adopt a balanced calendar for the remainder of the 2019-20 school year. The 2020-21 calendar previously was slated to start one week earlier (one week before Labor Day); however, that was always part of the plan even before the COVID-19 Pandemic.
